Lesson on structural equation modeling (SEM) in R- Dec 7 2017

In this script, I cover some basics of SEM in R, specifically SEM with observed variables. The script and slides focus on developing models, and understanding model construction.

This script was developed using some online tutorials and R-code available from Dr.Â Jarret Byrnes and Bill Shipley. To get help in other types of SEM, and use of other packages (e.g., lavaan) check the references and links below:

  • Jarret Byrnes tutorials
  • Shipley 2009. Confirmatory path analysis paper Usefult to perform path analysis with categorical or presence/absence data)
  • Shipley, B. 2016. Cause and correlation in biology: a userâs guide to path analysis, structural equations and causal inference with R. Cambridge University Press.
  • Grace, James B. Structural equation modeling and natural systems. Cambridge University Press, 2006.
  • Piecewise SEM package Useful to learn model specification and run SEMs with no-continuous data.

##############################
#Moving to SEM
##############################

#Refit the new cover relationship
fullMedLM<-lm(cover ~ firesev, data=keeley)
summary(fullMedLM)$r.squared
## [1] 0.1910867
lm.beta(fullMedLM)
##    firesev 
## -0.4371346
keeley$fireCoverResiduals<-residuals(fullMedLM)
residLM<-lm(fireCoverResiduals ~ age, data=keeley)
Anova(residLM)
## Anova Table (Type II tests)
## 
## Response: fireCoverResiduals
##           Sum Sq Df F value Pr(>F)
## age       0.2070  1  2.5876 0.1113
## Residuals 7.0383 88
plot(fireCoverResiduals ~ age, data=keeley)

################################
### SEM for Exercise
################################

#fit the pieces
abioticLM <- lm(abiotic ~ distance, data=keeley)
heteroLM <- lm(hetero ~ distance, data=keeley)
richnessLM <- lm(rich ~ abiotic + distance + hetero, data=keeley)

#evaluate the pieces
